  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      This is a pilot study to evaluate a restraint device for lumbar punctures. Designed to help
      improve the restraint techniques for lumbar puncture, the restraint device will be compared
      to the current standard of manual physical restraint in neonatal and pediatric patients (age
      1 day to 90 days of life). The investigators will study 30 subjects, with 20 randomized for
      the experimental device and 10 randomized for the &quot;control&quot; group, which is current standard
      of care. The investigators' primary outcomes will include time of procedure, red blood cells
      in the cerebrospinal fluid as well as physician satisfaction. Subjects will be eligible if
      they are 1-90 days of life, and their treating physician believes lumbar puncture is
      indicated. There is no follow-up once the lumbar puncture has been completed and the data has
      been obtained.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
